subject.Citations: People with HIV had higher overall unadjusted rates for all health conditions compared to those without diagnosed HIV
subject.Table: Prevalence of health outcomes, unadjusted means and odds ratios reported
subject.Footnotes: Each individual appears in this table once; in columns one through three it is at age 65, in column 4 it is in 2016 (in which upper age is trimmed at 98 years to avoid the impact of outliers who predominantly do not have HIV). Significance of the differences between (1) and (2) were calculated for each row using a chi-squared test. Not shown are controls for age, race/ethnicity, sex, state, rural/urban residence, and dual enrollment in Medicaid. The omitted group is White, urban, non-Medicaid enrolled males between the age of 65 and 74. Individuals are weighted using probability weights to reflect differential selection probabilities based on HIV diagnosis. 95% confidence intervals are reported in parentheses. Significance levels are shown with *** p-value<0.001, ** p-value < 0.01, and * p-value < 0.05. Each cell in (4) is a coefficient from a different model. Significance levels have been adjusted using the Bonferroni correction for multiple hypothesis testing to reflect 11 tests
